<!-- ─────────────────────── PAGE 10: DAYS 8-14 ─────────────────────── -->
<div class="page">
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="eyebrow">Chapter V</div>
    <h1 class="display">Days 8–14</h1>
    <h2 class="display">The wave</h2>

    <p>Week two is when something interesting happens: the craving wave becomes predictable. You'll start to notice that it comes at the same times, in the same situations. That's not a sign it's getting worse — that's a sign you're getting better at noticing it.</p>

    <h3>When does the wave hit?</h3>
    <p>Common patterns people report:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Late afternoon (3–5pm):</strong> the most common. Your energy is low. The day felt long. Your willpower is depleted.</li>
      <li><strong>After meals:</strong> especially dinner. The ritual of "winding down" used to include the thing. Now it doesn't.</li>
      <li><strong>When you're alone:</strong> idle time is the craving's favorite time.</li>
      <li><strong>Friday and Saturday evenings:</strong> the social conditioning is strong. The weekend used to mean something.</li>
      <li><strong>After a fight, a bad day, or news that hits hard:</strong> you used to numb. Now you have to feel it.</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="callout">
      <div class="label">The most useful thing you'll learn in week two</div>
      <p>The wave doesn't last. It comes, it peaks, it goes. From the moment you notice it to the moment it peaks is usually less than ten minutes. If you can stay on the other side of ten minutes, you will not use tonight. Not because you're strong. Because that's how the wave works.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="folio">V · Days 8–14</div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ─────────────────────── PAGE 11: HOW TO RIDE A WAVE ─────────────────────── -->
<div class="page">
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="eyebrow">Chapter V (continued)</div>
    <h1 class="display" style="font-size:24pt">How to ride a wave</h1>
    <h2 class="display">The expanded version</h2>

    <p>When the wave comes, the five moves below — in this order — are the ones that work for most people, most of the time. Don't try to do all five. Pick the one that feels most possible in the moment.</p>

    <ol class="number-list">
      <li><span><strong>Notice.</strong> "There it is." Just naming it out loud — "I'm having a craving" — shifts you slightly out of it.</span></li>
      <li><span><strong>Don't argue.</strong> "I shouldn't want this" makes it louder. "I want this and I'm not going to" makes it quieter.</span></li>
      <li><span><strong>Move.</strong> Stand up. Change rooms. Cold water on your face. Walk to the mailbox and back. The wave can't follow a moving body as easily.</span></li>
      <li><span><strong>Reach.</strong> Text someone. Don't explain. Just: "I'm having a wave." They'll know what you mean.</span></li>
      <li><span><strong>Wait.</strong> Set a 10-minute timer. Do anything else. When it rings, you'll be on the other side.</span></li>
    </ol>

    <div class="callout">
      <div class="label">If the wave keeps coming back</div>
      <p>It will. The wave doesn't obey rules. When it returns, repeat. Notice, don't argue, move, reach, wait. Most people need to do this 3-5 times in a day on the worst days. That's not failure. That's the work.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="folio">V · How to ride a wave</div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ─────────────────────── PAGE 12: DAYS 8-14 (CONTINUED) ─────────────────────── -->
<div class="page">
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="eyebrow">Chapter V (continued)</div>
    <h1 class="display" style="font-size:24pt">Sleep, energy, mood</h1>

    <p>Around day 10-14, your sleep will start to settle. Not perfectly — but noticeably. A few things to expect:</p>

    <h3>The sleep reset</h3>
    <p>You've probably been sleeping poorly for a while. Either too much, too little, or at the wrong times. Your body is recalibrating. For the first 2-3 weeks, accept that sleep will be uneven. By week three, you should be falling asleep within 30 minutes of trying and waking up feeling roughly rested.</p>

    <h3>The mood flatline</h3>
    <p>A lot of people describe week two as feeling <em>numb</em>. Not high, not low. Just flat. This is your brain's reward system coming back online. It's recalibrating. The flatness is not depression. It's the absence of the artificial spikes the substance gave you. Give it two more weeks.</p>

    <h3>Energy in the morning</h3>
    <p>If you can, get 10-15 minutes of sunlight in the first hour after waking. This resets your circadian rhythm. Walk, sit on a porch, drink your coffee by a window. Doesn't matter what you do — just light on your face.</p>

    <h3>The trap of "I'm fine now"</h3>
    <p>Around day 10, you'll have a day where you feel great. Energized. Clear. You'll think: "I'm past this. I don't need the toolkit anymore. I don't need to be careful." That's the most dangerous day. The wave is least expected because you stopped bracing for it. Stay in the toolkit. Stay humble. The wave doesn't care how good you feel.</p>

    <div class="pull-quote">The day you feel most like you don't need help is the day you need it most.</div>

    <div class="callout">
      <div class="label">A small but important thing</div>
      <p>If you have a pet — a dog, a cat — and you can let them sleep near you, do that this week. There's no science paper that proves it, and it doesn't matter. Having another living thing breathing next to you changes the 3am room.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="folio">V · Days 8–14</div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ─────────────────────── PAGE 12: DAYS 15-21 ─────────────────────── -->
<div class="page">
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="eyebrow">Chapter VI</div>
    <h1 class="display">Days 15–21</h1>
    <h2 class="display">The people</h2>

    <p>The first two weeks were about you. Week three is about the people around you — and how you let them in.</p>

    <h3>Who to tell</h3>
    <p>By now you know who the safe people are. The ones who don't flinch. The ones who ask "how are you" and actually want the answer. Tell one more of them. Not all of them. One more. Just so you have a second person on the list.</p>

    <h3>Who not to tell yet</h3>
    <p>The person who'll make it about them. The person who'll tell you about their cousin who "also quit and it was fine." The person who'll want you to explain your whole story at a dinner party. You don't owe them a status update. You don't owe them a story. "I'm taking a break" is enough.</p>

    <h3>What to do about people who still use</h3>
    <p>This is the hardest conversation you'll have. You have at least one relationship that orbits around the substance. The bar you went to. The friend you called when you ran out. The family member who always offered.</p>

    <p>You don't have to cut everyone off forever. But for the first 90 days, you do need to be away from the situations. The relationships that aren't the substance — the actual friend — those will still be there in 90 days. You can rebuild them. For now, protect the work.</p>

    <h3>The friend who says "just have one"</h3>
    <p>They mean well. They don't understand. They think you're being dramatic. You don't have to explain. You just have to keep not having one. Eventually they forget. Most of them do.</p>

    <div class="callout" style="break-before: page;">
      <div class="label">About the people who hurt you</div>
      <p>Recovery will start to show you the people who hurt you while you were using. People who used you. People who let you use. People who needed you to keep using so they could feel better about themselves. This is normal. It is also not work for week three. When it comes up, write it down, and bring it to a therapist or a meeting when you're ready. Not yet.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="folio">VI · Days 15–21</div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ─────────────────────── PAGE 13: DAYS 15-21 (CONTINUED) ─────────────────────── -->
<div class="page">
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="eyebrow">Chapter VI (continued)</div>
    <h1 class="display" style="font-size:24pt; break-before: page;">Asking for help</h1>

    <p>By week three, the "I can do this alone" story starts to crack. That's good. Here's how to ask for help without making it a whole production.</p>

    <h3>The minimum viable ask</h3>
    <p>You don't have to ask for a twelve-step commitment. You just have to ask for one of these:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>"Can you check in on me tomorrow morning?"</li>
      <li>"Can you be around at 5pm? That's my wave time."</li>
      <li>"Can you just listen for three minutes? I don't need you to fix it."</li>
      <li>"I'm having a hard day. I don't need anything, I just wanted you to know."</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>What to do when someone asks how you're doing</h3>
    <p>You don't have to perform. You can say:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>"I'm on day 17. It's a hard day." (That's a complete sentence.)</li>
      <li>"I'm okay-ish." (They don't need more than that.)</li>
      <li>"I'd rather not get into it right now." (Boundaries are allowed.)</li>
      <li>"Can we talk about something else?" (Sometimes you just need to feel normal.)</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>When to find a meeting (if you haven't)</h3>
    <p>By day 21, if you haven't been to a meeting, find one. Not because meetings are the only way. Because you need to be in a room with people who understand. You don't have to share. You don't have to commit. You just have to show up.</p>

    <p>Online options if in-person feels like too much:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>SMART Recovery online meetings (secular, science-based)</li>
      <li>Recovery Dharma (Buddhist-informed, non-theistic)</li>
      <li>Women for Sobriety (if applicable)</li>
      <li>r/stopdrinking on Reddit (not a meeting, but a real community)</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="pull-quote">Asking for help is not a sign of weakness. It's the only sign that the work is real.</div>

    <div class="folio">VI · Days 15–21</div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ─────────────────────── PAGE 14: DAYS 22-30 ─────────────────────── -->
<div class="page">
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="eyebrow">Chapter VII</div>
    <h1 class="display">Days 22–30</h1>
    <h2 class="display">The foundation</h2>

    <p>You're almost at thirty. The thing you couldn't imagine at day one is happening: you're a person who has done this for almost a month. Now is when you start building the version of your life that doesn't revolve around the substance.</p>

    <h3>Build a routine, not a personality</h3>
    <p>Don't try to become a "sober person." Become a person with a routine that makes sense. The routine is what carries you when motivation leaves. Motivation is unreliable. Routine isn't.</p>

    <h3 style="break-before: page;">The minimum viable week</h3>
    <p>If you only do four things each week, do these:</p>
    <ol class="number-list">
      <li><span><strong>One morning ritual</strong> — same time, same place, same three actions. Every day.</span></li>
      <li><span><strong>One body movement</strong> — walk, lift, stretch, dance, swim. 20 minutes. Same day of the week if possible.</span></li>
      <li><span><strong>One connection</strong> — phone call, coffee, message, meeting. With another human. Every week.</span></li>
      <li><span><strong>One check-in with yourself</strong> — five minutes, paper, "what's working, what isn't." Every Sunday.</span></li>
    </ol>

    <h3>What you can stop doing now</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>You can stop counting the days. You can stop saying "I'm on day X." You're just living.</li>
      <li>You can stop explaining yourself. "I'm taking a break" becomes unnecessary. Just "no thank you."</li>
      <li>You can stop being at the meeting every day. You can taper down. Two a week. Then one.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>What you should keep doing</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Stay in the morning ritual.</li>
      <li>Keep one person who knows, who you can text at 3am.</li>
      <li>Notice the voice. It gets quieter but it doesn't disappear.</li>
      <li>Eat well. Sleep. Move. The boring stuff is the actual work.</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="folio">VII · Days 22–30</div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ─────────────────────── PAGE 15: THE HONEST TRUTH ─────────────────────── -->
<div class="page">
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="eyebrow">Chapter VII (continued)</div>
    <h1 class="display" style="font-size:24pt">The honest truth</h1>
    <h2 class="display">About day 30</h2>

    <div class="callout">
      <div class="label">What day 30 actually means</div>
      <p>Day 30 doesn't fix anything. You're not "cured." You're not safe. The substance is still out there, the people who use are still using, the voice still visits. What day 30 does is prove to you that you can do this — not perfectly, not easily, but you can do it.</p>
      <p>That's enough. Don't ask day 30 to be a finish line. It's a checkpoint.</p>
    </div>

    <p>The people who make it past day 30 usually do it because of one of three things: a morning ritual that holds them when motivation doesn't, at least one person who knows what they're going through, and a willingness to be uncomfortable without numbing.</p>

    <p>You have those. You're using one of them right now — reading this guide.</p>

    <div class="folio">VII · Honest truth</div>
  </div>
</div>

