<!-- ─────────────────────── PAGE 17: MORNING RITUAL ─────────────────────── -->
<div class="page">
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="eyebrow">Worksheet · VII</div>
    <h1 class="display" style="font-size:24pt">My morning ritual</h1>

    <div class="worksheet">
      <div class="worksheet-title">Worksheet · My Morning Ritual</div>
      <div class="worksheet-sub">Pick three things. Same time, same place, every day. The boring-er the better.</div>

      <div class="checklist-item"><span class="check"></span><span>Water before coffee</span></div>
      <div class="checklist-item"><span class="check"></span><span>10 minutes of light (outside, window, porch)</span></div>
      <div class="checklist-item"><span class="check"></span><span>One sentence about how I feel (paper, voice memo, app)</span></div>
      <div class="checklist-item"><span class="check"></span><span>Move my body for 5 minutes (stretch, walk, stairs)</span></div>
      <div class="checklist-item"><span class="check"></span><span>Eat one real thing (not just coffee)</span></div>
      <div class="checklist-item"><span class="check"></span><span>Phone stays in another room for the first 30 minutes</span></div>
      <div class="checklist-item"><span class="check"></span><span>One thing I'm grateful for (specific, not generic)</span></div>
      <div class="checklist-item"><span class="check"></span><span>Look at my trigger list (if I have one)</span></div>
      <div class="checklist-item"><span class="check"></span><span>Something else I invented:</span></div>
      <div style="height:10pt"></div>
    </div>

    <div class="callout">
      <div class="label">The morning ritual works because</div>
      <p>the hardest craving moment of the day is around 4pm, not the morning. The morning ritual isn't about the morning — it's about building a small win before the day starts. Win the morning and the day starts at 60% instead of 0%.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="folio">VII · My morning ritual</div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ─────────────────────── PAGE 18: TOOLKIT ─────────────────────── -->
<div class="page">
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="eyebrow">Chapter VIII</div>
    <h1 class="display">When the urge hits</h1>
    <h2 class="display">Your full toolkit</h2>

    <p>Print this page. Stick it on the fridge. When the wave comes, you'll have it in front of you.</p>

    <h3>The 5-minute wave</h3>
    <ol class="number-list">
      <li><span><strong>Name it out loud.</strong> "I'm having a craving." Shifts you from inside it to next to it.</span></li>
      <li><span><strong>One deep breath cycle.</strong> 4 in, hold 7, out 8. Just one. Or four if you can.</span></li>
      <li><span><strong>Cold water.</strong> Face, wrists, back of neck. Or hold an ice cube. Cold breaks the loop.</span></li>
      <li><span><strong>Stand up and move.</strong> Walk to another room. Walk to the mailbox. Walk back. The wave can't follow.</span></li>
      <li><span><strong>Set a 10-minute timer.</strong> Do anything else. The wave will be smaller when the timer rings.</span></li>
    </ol>

    <div class="callout">
      <div class="label">If the 5-minute moves aren't enough</div>
      <p>Turn to the next page. There you'll find the longer moves, the wave-that-won't-break plan, and the crisis resources. None of this is a substitute for calling someone — but the next page gives you more tools when the small ones don't reach.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="folio">VIII · When the urge hits</div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ─────────────────────── PAGE 18: 30-MIN WAVE ─────────────────────── -->
<div class="page">
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="eyebrow">Chapter VIII (continued)</div>
    <h1 class="display" style="font-size:22pt">The 30-minute wave</h1>

    <p>When the 5-minute moves don't work — or the wave is bigger than usual — reach for one of these. You don't need to do all five. One is enough.</p>

    <ol class="number-list">
      <li><span><strong>Call someone.</strong> Voice, not text. From your list. They don't need to say anything wise. They just need to be there.</span></li>
      <li><span><strong>Eat something.</strong> Anything. Bread, fruit, leftovers, cereal. The body interprets low blood sugar as craving.</span></li>
      <li><span><strong>Leave the house.</strong> Even for 15 minutes. The library, a park, a coffee shop, a walk around the block.</span></li>
      <li><span><strong>Shower or bath.</strong> Hot if you can. The body resets when the temperature changes.</span></li>
      <li><span><strong>Play a song you love.</strong> All the way through. Don't skip. Let it finish.</span></li>
    </ol>

    <h3>The wave that won't break</h3>
    <p>If you've done all of the above and the wave is still there, that's when you reach for:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>A meeting.</strong> Online if in-person feels like too much. SMART Recovery, Recovery Dharma, r/stopdrinking.</li>
      <li><strong>A crisis line.</strong> 988 in the US, 741741 by text. These exist for this.</li>
      <li><strong>A medical professional.</strong> If the physical symptoms are severe (shaking, vomiting, hallucinations), go to a clinic.</li>
    </ul>

    <div class="crisis">
      <div class="crisis-title">If you are in immediate danger</div>
      <p><strong>Call 911</strong> · <strong>988</strong> (Suicide & Crisis Lifeline, US) · <strong>Text HOME to 741741</strong> · <strong>findahelpline.com</strong> (international)</p>
    </div>

    <div class="folio">VIII (cont.) · The 30-minute wave</div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ─────────────────────── PAGE 19: IF YOU SLIP ─────────────────────── -->
<div class="page">
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="eyebrow">Chapter IX</div>
    <h1 class="display">If you slip</h1>
    <h2 class="display">What to do next</h2>

    <p>If you're reading this because you used, or you're about to, or you're scared you might — that's the right place to be. This is the most important chapter in this guide.</p>

    <div class="pull-quote">A slip is not a relapse. A slip is data.</div>

    <h3>What just happened</h3>
    <p>You used. The wave got bigger than your tools. That's not failure — that's information. Something in your plan didn't account for what just happened. Now you know.</p>

    <h3>The next hour, then tomorrow morning</h3>
    <p><strong>This hour:</strong> water, food, blanket, breathe. Do not make any big decisions. Not "I should give up." Not "I should reset." The big decisions can wait until tomorrow.</p>

    <p><strong>Tomorrow morning:</strong> water, breakfast, then text one person. Not the whole list — one. "I had a slip last night. I'm okay. Just wanted you to know." That's the whole message.</p>

    <p><strong>Do NOT reset your counter.</strong> You didn't lose 17 days. You used once. Those are different things. Zeroing the counter is the single biggest predictor of a full relapse.</p>

    <p><strong>Within a day or two:</strong> write down what happened — the time of day, who you were with, what triggered it. And reach out to one professional. Not because you're broken — because they have tools you don't.</p>

    <div class="callout">
      <div class="label">A note about shame</div>
      <p>Shame is the most expensive feeling in recovery. It doesn't help. It doesn't teach. It doesn't protect. It just makes you hide, and hiding is when the next slip happens. The opposite of shame is not "no shame" — it's honesty. Tell one person. That's the cure.</p>
    </div>

    <h3>One slip is not a verdict</h3>
    <p>If you've used once in 17 days, you've used 1 out of 17 days. That's a 94% success rate. If you used once in 30 days, that's a 97% success rate. The story your brain tells ("I'm back to zero, I should just give up") is a lie. The story your numbers tell is true.</p>

    <div class="folio">IX · If you slip</div>
  </div>
</div>

<!-- ─────────────────────── PAGE 20: AFTER DAY 30 ─────────────────────── -->
<div class="page">
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="eyebrow">Chapter X</div>
    <h1 class="display">After day 30</h1>
    <h2 class="display">What comes next</h2>

    <p>If you've made it to day 30 — whether it's been one day, three months, or three years since your last use — you have something most people don't: proof that you can do this.</p>

    <h3>What's different after 30 days</h3>
    <p>Less than you think. The substance is still out there. The voice still visits. The people who use are still using. What is different is that <em>you</em> are different. You have thirty days of proof that the wave comes and goes. That's the only real asset you have in recovery. Protect it.</p>

    <h3 style="break-before: page;">What to do for the next 60 days</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>Keep the morning ritual. Don't let it erode.</li>
      <li>Keep at least one connection — meeting, friend, professional.</li>
      <li>Stay aware of your triggers. The map changes over time.</li>
      <li>Don't take on big life decisions in the first 90 days. Stay steady.</li>
      <li>If you had a slip, get back on the horse the same day. Don't reset, don't quit, don't negotiate.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>What the next 90 days actually look like</h3>
    <p>Days 30-60 feel mostly stable, with occasional waves you can ride. Days 60-90 is when you start to feel like yourself again — except with more self-knowledge than you've had in years. The people who make it to 90 have a 60% chance of making it to a year. The people who make it to a year have an 85% chance of making it to five years. You're closer than you think.</p>

    <div class="pull-quote">You didn't come this far to only come this far.</div>

    <div class="callout">
      <div class="label">When you meet someone at day 1</div>
      <p>Remember what it felt like to read this guide. When you meet someone at their day 1, you don't have to say anything wise. You just have to remember. The rest takes care of itself.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="folio">X · After day 30</div>
  </div>
</div>

